    "The numbers of nucleotide sequences per Molecular Cancer paper also rose significantly from 2014 to 2020 (Fig. 4B).",
    "It seems possible that as the numbers of nucleotide sequence reagents per paper increase, more papers could describe wrongly identified sequences.",
    "However, we noted that the median numbers of wrongly identified sequences per Molecular Cancer paper were largely stable across 2014-2020, and no significant correlation was measured between wrongly identified and overall nucleotide sequence numbers.",
    "Median numbers of wrongly identified sequences in Molecular Cancer and Oncogene papers were also similar to those noted for papers in lower IF journals (Park et al. 2022).",
    "This suggests that the rising proportions of erroneous Molecular Cancer papers from 2014 to 2020 do not simply reflect the publication of increasingly complex papers during this time."
